Hmm.. I am pretty sure that almost anytime you sign a contract here in the US (and an insurance agreement/application is a legally binding contract) the person presenting the contract is required to explain everything you don't understand and ask them to explain to you about that contract.. I may be mistaken.. it's happened once or twice.  <br>
<br>
In any case, you can also go down to the department of insurance (or whatever state department handles insurance regulation in your state.. they ALL have to regulate it) and ask for documentation or ask for places to get information on insurance.  Libraries are also a good place to look.  I make it a point to know as much as I can about anything that I give that amount of money to <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Gurg V1.0</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeenmalikyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen MaliKyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 100<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/11/02 9:05:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3712.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: insurance</span><hr size=1> Gurg, you are correct about going to the Department of Insurance to get information. The state's Insurance Commissioner can tell you which companies are the best at paying claims, too.<br>
<br>
You may be right about: <i>"...the person presenting the contract is required to explain everything you don't understand and ask them to explain to you about that contract..."</i>. <br>
<br>
It has been 10 years since I was an insurance agent and things probably have changed. When I was an agent we only where legally held to explaining what was <i>material</i> to a customer's question. In other words, the burden of proof that a customer didn't understand parts of the contract was upon the customer.<br>
<br>
Infact, that is where insurance companies can be really evil. Insurance companies have a signed contract where the customer acknowledges they understand the terms of the contract, but the insured really has no recourse if they have to prove that the Insurer's agent either misrepresented or omitted information in order to get a sale.<br>
<br>
I personally knew agents who would have customers sign life insurance contracts at the same time they were buying auto insurance and the customer didn't know they were getting life insurance! One of these people had called my office wanting an auto quote and they practically had a heart attack when the price was so much different. When I reviewed their portfolio with them they were aghast that they were sold a life insurance policy with no knowledge of what they had.<br>
<br>
I know that some agents can be pretty da<i></i>mn sneaky to say the least, not the majority of them... just a few really smelly bad apples.<br>
